'''Edinburgh University Highland Society''' (Scottish Gaelic ''Comann Ceilteach Oilthigh Dhùn Èideann'') is the [[Gaelic language]] and [[Celts|Celtic]] Studies society at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. Established in 1851, it the oldest society at the University. It is the successor organization to the short-lived Ossianic Society, which was founded in 1837.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Crouse|first1=L.A.|title=The establishment of Celtic Societies|journal=[[History Scotland]]|issue=Sept/Oct 2013|pages=24–31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=MacCoinnich|first1=Aonghas|title=19th & 20th C: Ossianic Society|url=https://sgeulnagaidhlig.ac.uk/ossianic-society/?lang=en|website=The Gaelic Story at the University of Glasgow|publisher=University of Glasgow|accessdate=19 April 2018|date=3 March 2016}}</ref>

The 'Highland Society' is the current official name registered with [[Edinburgh University Students' Association]], although during its existence it has also been known as Edinburgh University Celtic Society, the literal translation of the Gaelic name.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}

The Society runs the Highland Annual Ball (Scottish Gaelic ''An Dannsa Bliadhnail'') each spring, a [[ceilidh]] for students and the wider Edinburgh Gaelic community which has been a prominent fixture of the Gaelic calendar in the city for many decades.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Highland Society|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/about/gaelic/the-highland-society|website=The University of Edinburgh|publisher=University of Edinburgh|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>

