{{Use American English|date=March 2015}}
The '''Welner table''' is a medical [[examination table]] designed to facilitate [[accessibility]] for both patients and doctors with [[physical disability|physical disabilities]]. It was designed by American [[obstetrician]]-[[gynecologist]] and [[disability rights]] activist [[Sandra Welner]].

Welner's work with disabled women patients led her to invent the Welner table, a [[universal design|universally accessible]] examination table with a wider than usual range of adjustments in position and height, down to as low as {{convert|20|in}} above floor level for easier transfers from a [[wheelchair]].<ref name=Courant>{{cite news |url=http://articles.courant.com/1998-03-03/features/9803030035_1_disabilities-health-care-clinics |date=1998-03-03 |first=Hilary |last=Waldman |title=New Equipment, New Outlook|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]}}</ref> The table also serves the needs of disabled physicians by allowing a wider range of positions for performing examinations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/obituaries/20011023welner1023p2.asp |title=Obituary: Dr. Sandra Welner / Obstetrician-gynecologist, champion for disabled women |date=2001-10-23 |first=Anita |last=Srikameswaran |newspaper=Post-Gazette}}</ref><ref name=Courant/>

